        // ── New Lead Fork (Article) ──────────────────────────────────────
        await GetOrCreateModule(new TrainingModule
        {
            Title = "Adding a Lead: Engagement Shapes",
            Slug = "leads-new-lead-fork",
            Summary = "How the New Lead dialog works: pick an engagement shape (Quick add, Quick quote/RFQ, Repeat, Strategic, Prototype) and fill the shape-specific fields tailored to that sales motion.",
            ContentType = TrainingContentType.Article,
            EstimatedMinutes = 5,
            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 5,
            AppRoutes = """["/leads"]""",
            Tags = """["leads","sales","intake"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## Adding a Lead: Engagement Shapes\n\nWhen you click **New Lead** on the Leads page, you don't land on a flat form anymore. A two-step fork dialog opens that first asks *what kind of opportunity this is*, then surfaces a base form plus a few extra fields tailored to that sales motion. Picking the right shape up front means you capture the context that actually matters for that kind of deal — without burying every lead under fields most of them don't need.\n\n### Step 1 — Pick the Engagement Shape\n\nThe dialog opens on the question \"What kind of opportunity is this?\" with five cards:\n\n- **Quick add** (flash icon) — Just the basics: company, contact, source. Skip the extras and tailor later. This is the fastest path and matches the old flat dialog. Pick this when you only have a name and want to get the lead into the system now.\n- **Quick quote / RFQ** (request-quote icon) — An inbound request with a formed need. Surfaces a parts/quantities list, a target due date (\"Needed by\"), and a target price. Use this when a prospect already knows what they want quoted.\n- **Repeat / standing relationship** (repeat icon) — An existing customer-shaped lead. Surfaces a reference-job field so you can point at the prior job number, PO, or work order this should reference.\n- **Strategic account** (business-center icon) — A long sales cycle with multiple stakeholders. Surfaces decision-maker, champion, and current-vendor fields so the account context travels with the lead.\n- **Prototype / R&D** (science icon) — Custom or exploratory work. Surfaces the RFQ fields *plus* project type and expected timeline.\n\nClicking a card advances you to Step 2.\n\n### Step 2 — Fill the Form\n\nEvery shape lands on the same base fields — the same set the rest of the Leads module uses:\n\n- **Company Name** (required) — the prospect company. This becomes the Customer name on conversion.\n- **Contact Name**, **Email**, **Phone** — the person you're working with. Email is validated as an email address if you fill it.\n- **Source** — how the lead found you, from the configurable lead-source list.\n- **Follow-Up Date** — can't be in the past.\n- **Account** — optionally link this lead to a B2B Account (a multi-contact parent grouping). You can create a new Account inline with the **New Account** button without leaving the dialog.\n- **Notes** — free-form context.\n\nBelow the base fields, an accented **extras** section appears *only* when the shape you picked has shape-specific fields. Quick add shows no extras section at all — that's by design, it keeps the fast path fast.\n\n### Shape-Specific Extra Fields\n\n| Shape | Extra fields captured |\n|---|---|\n| Quick add | (none) |\n| Quick quote / RFQ | Parts / quantities, Target price, Needed-by date |\n| Repeat | Reference job (prior job #, PO, or work order) |\n| Strategic | Decision maker, Champion, Current vendor |\n| Prototype / R&D | Parts / quantities, Target price, Needed-by date, Project type, Expected timeline |\n\nThese extras are stored on the lead as custom field values (a JSONB bag), so the team can add new shapes over time without a schema change. Only fields you actually fill are saved — empty extras are dropped.\n\n### What Carries Forward\n\nThe shape you pick is stored on the lead as its **engagement shape**. On the lead detail panel, an engagement-signal strip uses that shape to show a short playbook hint reminding you what to do next for that kind of deal. The shape is guidance, not a hard gate — you can still work any lead through the normal New → Contacted → Quoting pipeline regardless of how it started.\n\n### Required Fields\n\nOnly **Company Name** is required, on every shape. Fields marked with an asterisk must be filled before the **Create lead** button enables; the validation button surfaces what's missing if you try to submit early. Everything else — including all the shape-specific extras — is optional and can be filled in later from the lead detail.\n\n### Back and Cancel\n\n**Back** returns you to the shape picker (Step 1) so you can change your mind about the shape. **Cancel** closes the dialog without creating anything. The dialog auto-saves a draft as you type, so an accidental close doesn't lose your work.","sections":[]}"""
        });

        // ── Bulk Intake (Walkthrough) ────────────────────────────────────
        await GetOrCreateModule(new TrainingModule
        {
            Title = "Leads Intake & Bulk Import",
