        // ── Call Queue (Article) ─────────────────────────────────────────
        await GetOrCreateModule(new TrainingModule
        {
            Title = "Working the Call Queue",
            Slug = "leads-call-queue",
            Summary = "The pull-based worker queue for high-volume outreach: pull a batch, dial leads, and disposition each with single-keystroke shortcuts.",
            ContentType = TrainingContentType.Article,
            EstimatedMinutes = 5,
            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 7,
            AppRoutes = """["/leads/queue"]""",
            Tags = """["leads","outreach","queue"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## Working the Call Queue\n\nThe Worker Queue (Leads → Queue) is built for high-volume outreach — when you're working through dozens of leads a session and need to move fast. Instead of scrolling a list and opening each lead, you **pull a slice** of leads and the queue serves them to you one at a time, with keyboard-driven dispositions that advance automatically.\n\n### Pulling a Batch\n\nWhen the queue is empty it shows a \"Ready to work\" card. Set the **Pull size** (1–50, default 5) and click **Pull next N**. The server hands you that many leads to work. Two reps pulling at the same time get *disjoint* slices — you'll never both land on the same lead, so there's no double-dialing.\n\nIf there's nothing to pull, the queue tells you so (\"No more leads to pull right now\") — check back later or work a different campaign.\n\n### The Lead Card\n\nEach lead is shown as a single focused card with a progress indicator (\"Lead 2 of 5\") at the top. The card surfaces what you need to make the call:\n\n- **Company name** and any **campaign** chip.\n- **Warning chips** — cooldown-until date, email opt-out, or call opt-out. These tell you immediately if a lead shouldn't be contacted on a given channel.\n- **Contact, email, source, last-activity, and notes** in a compact grid.\n- A **click-to-dial** button on the phone number. Clicking it places the call (today via a tel: link; the same hook supports softphone integrations later) and is wired to auto-log the interaction.\n- A **Disposition notes** box for anything worth recording about the call.\n\n### Dispositioning a Lead\n\nAfter the call, record the outcome. Six dispositions are available — each as a button *and* a single-keystroke shortcut:\n\n| Key | Disposition | What it does |\n|---|---|---|\n| **E** | Engaged | The lead exits the queue and flips to Contacted — you made a real connection. |\n| **N** | No answer | Re-queues the lead for a later retry. |\n| **V** | Voicemail left | Re-queues the lead for a later retry. |\n| **C** | Schedule callback | Opens a callback-scheduler dialog for a date and time; only commits once you confirm. |\n| **B** | Bad data | Marks the lead lost — wrong number, bounce, or disconnected line. |\n| **S** | Suppress (DNC) | Operator-initiated Do-Not-Contact; routes to the suppression list. |\n\nEvery disposition is one action, and the queue **automatically advances** to the next lead in your batch. The disposition notes you typed are attached, then cleared for the next lead.\n\n### Keyboard-First Navigation\n\nThe queue is designed to be worked without the mouse:\n\n- **E / N / V / C / B / S** fire the matching disposition.\n- **J** moves to the next lead in the batch; **K** moves to the previous one.\n- Shortcuts are ignored while you're typing in the notes box, so your typing is never intercepted.\n\nThe little keyboard badges on each button aren't decoration — they're the live shortcut keys.\n\n### When the Batch Is Exhausted\n\nWork through all the leads in your slice and the queue returns to the \"Ready to work\" card so you can pull the next batch. Nothing is lost between batches — each pull is a fresh, independent slice.\n\n### Where Dispositions Go\n\nEngaged leads become Contacted in the normal pipeline. No-answer and voicemail leads come back around for retry. Callback-scheduled leads carry their callback time. Bad-data leads are lost. Suppressed leads land on the Suppression / Do-Not-Contact list, where their opt-out can be reviewed or lifted later.","sections":[]}"""
        });

        // ── Outreach Campaigns (Article) ─────────────────────────────────
        await GetOrCreateModule(new TrainingModule
        {
            Title = "Outreach Campaigns",
            Slug = "leads-campaigns",
            Summary = "What outreach campaigns are, how they group bulk-import cohorts for reporting, and how to create and edit them.",
            ContentType = TrainingContentType.Article,
            EstimatedMinutes = 4,
            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 8,
            AppRoutes = """["/leads/campaigns"]""",
            Tags = """["leads","outreach","campaigns","marketing"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## Outreach Campaigns\n\nA **Campaign** wraps a batch of marketing leads into a named cohort so you can configure outreach once and report on results cleanly. When you bulk-import leads, every Lead gets a CampaignId so reporting can answer questions like \"How did the September LinkedIn batch perform versus August?\" without guessing.\n\nFind campaigns at **Leads → Campaigns**.\n\n### What a Campaign Carries\n\nA campaign holds the configuration shared by every lead in the cohort:\n\n- **Name** (required) — a human label for the cohort (e.g., \"IMTS 2026 Booth Scans\").\n- **Description** — free-form context about the campaign.\n- **Strategy** — the outreach motion (Cold Call, Cold Email, Trade Show Follow-up, Webinar Attendee, Purchased List, Manual Entry). The strategy is set at creation and isn't changed afterward, since it defines how leads in the cohort were sourced.\n- **Default cooldown override** — how many days (0–730) to wait before re-contacting a lead in this campaign, overriding the system default.\n- **Started / Ended dates** — the active window of the campaign.\n- **Active** flag — whether the campaign is currently running.\n\n### The Campaigns List\n\nThe list is a sortable table with columns for Name, Strategy, Leads (the count of leads in the cohort), Active status, Started date, and Created date. The Active column shows a green \"Active\" chip or a muted \"Inactive\" chip at a glance.\n\n### Creating a Campaign\n\nClick **New Campaign** in the page header. Fill in the name (required), an optional description, pick the strategy, optionally set a default cooldown override, and set the started/ended dates. Save and the campaign appears in the list.\n\nThe **Strategy** field only appears when creating — once leads are tied to a campaign under a given strategy, you don't switch it.\n\n### Editing a Campaign\n\nClick any row (or its edit icon) to open the edit dialog. You can update the name, description, cooldown override, and dates, and toggle the **Active** flag to pause or resume the campaign. The strategy is read-only in edit mode.\n\n### How Campaigns Connect to Intake and Leads\n\nCampaigns are the reporting backbone for bulk outreach:\n\n- On the **Bulk Intake** page you can tag an import batch with a campaign so the imported leads roll up to it.\n- On a **lead's detail panel**, a campaign chip shows which campaign produced the lead and links straight to the Campaigns page. That chip is read-only on the lead — the campaign is the source of record, set at intake, not reassigned from the lead.\n- The **default cooldown override** flows through to the suppression/cooldown logic for leads in the campaign, so re-contact timing respects the campaign's policy.","sections":[]}"""
        });

        // ── Accounts & Bulk-Assign (Article) ─────────────────────────────
        await GetOrCreateModule(new TrainingModule
        {
            Title = "Accounts & Bulk-Assigning Leads",
            Slug = "leads-accounts",
            Summary = "B2B Accounts group multiple contacts under one parent company; how to create accounts, link leads to them, and bulk-assign many leads at once.",
            ContentType = TrainingContentType.Article,
            EstimatedMinutes = 4,
            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 9,
            AppRoutes = """["/leads/accounts","/leads"]""",
            Tags = """["leads","accounts","b2b"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## Accounts & Bulk-Assigning Leads\n\n**Accounts** are multi-contact B2B parent groupings. When one prospect company has several people you're working — an engineer, a procurement contact, an executive sponsor — a single Lead row would force you to pick which contact to surface. An Account lets all of those leads roll up under one company umbrella instead.\n\nFind accounts at **Leads → Accounts**.\n\n### What an Account Holds\n\nAn account describes the parent company:\n\n- **Account name** (required), **Industry**, **Size bracket**.\n- **Address** — city, state, postal code, country.\n- **Website**, **Phone**, **Description**.\n\nThe accounts list table shows Name, Industry, Size, City, State, a **Contacts** count, a **Leads** count (how many leads point at this account), and the created date.\n\n### Creating an Account\n\nClick **New Account** in the toolbar, fill in the name (required) and any company details, and save. You can also create an account *inline* from the New Lead dialog's account picker — click **New Account** there to add one without leaving the lead you're creating.\n\n### Linking a Lead to an Account\n\nThere are two ways a lead gets tied to an account:\n\n1. **At intake** — the New Lead fork dialog has an Account picker. Pick an existing account, or create one inline.\n2. **In bulk** — from the main Leads list, select multiple leads and assign them to an account in one action (below).\n\nWhen a linked lead is later converted to a Customer, the account's contacts roll forward as non-primary contacts on the resulting Customer record, so the relationship survives conversion.\n\n### Bulk-Assigning Leads to an Account\n\nOn the main **Leads** list (table view), each row has a checkbox. Select one or more leads and a **bulk action bar** appears at the top of the table showing how many are selected. Click **Assign Account**, pick the target account in the dialog (you can create a new one inline here too), and confirm. Every selected lead is linked to that account in one operation.\n\nThis is the fast way to organize a pile of freshly imported leads — select the ones that belong to the same parent company and assign them together.\n\n### Deleting an Account\n\nDeleting an account is a soft delete. The server **blocks** deletion while any lead still references the account — you'll get a message telling you how many leads are linked. Unassign the account on those leads first, then retry. Already-converted leads are unaffected by an account deletion.","sections":[]}"""
        });

        // ── Sample Shipment Tracking (Article) ───────────────────────────
        await GetOrCreateModule(new TrainingModule
        {
            Title = "Sample Shipment Tracking",
            Slug = "leads-samples",
            Summary = "The cross-lead view of pre-quote sample parts: the sample lifecycle, status filtering, advancing samples, and recording outcomes.",
            ContentType = TrainingContentType.Article,
            EstimatedMinutes = 4,
            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 10,
            AppRoutes = """["/leads/samples"]""",
            Tags = """["leads","samples","presales"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## Sample Shipment Tracking\n\nBefore a quote is firm, you often send a prospect a **sample part** to evaluate. The Sample Shipments page (Leads → Samples) is the cross-lead read view of every sample in flight — so sales managers can spot stale samples (delivered but no follow-up quote) and reps can see where each prospect sits in the sample-evaluation loop.\n\n### What the List Shows\n\nThe table lists every sample across all leads, with columns for the **Lead** it belongs to, **Part** description, **Quantity**, **Status**, the **Requested / Shipped / Delivered** dates, **Cost** to us, and the **Tracking** number (carrier + tracking). Clicking a row opens that sample's lead detail.\n\n### The Sample Lifecycle\n\nA sample moves through a linear lifecycle, then ends in one of three outcomes:\n\n1. **Requested** — a sample has been asked for.\n2. **Approved** — the request is approved to send.\n3. **Shipped** — the sample is on its way (a ship date is stamped).\n4. **Delivered** — the prospect has it (a delivery date is stamped).\n\nThen an outcome:\n\n- **Quoted** (Quoted from sample) — the sample led to a quote. Success.\n- **Lost** (Lost from sample) — the sample didn't convert.\n- **Stale** — delivered but went quiet with no follow-up.\n\n### Advancing a Sample\n\nThe linear steps move forward one at a time. On each row, an **advance arrow** moves the sample to its next status — Requested → Approved → Shipped → Delivered. Advancing to Shipped or Delivered stamps the matching date automatically. Once a sample reaches Delivered (or an outcome), there's no further advance arrow.\n\n### Recording an Outcome\n\nOutcome states need operator intent, so they live behind the row's **outcome menu** (the three-dot button) rather than the advance arrow:\n\n- **Mark Quoted from sample** — the sample produced a quote.\n- **Mark Lost from sample** — it didn't convert.\n- **Mark Stale** — manually flag it as gone cold.\n\nNote that **Stale** is also set automatically by a nightly job for delivered samples that go quiet, so you usually don't have to mark it by hand.\n\n### Filtering\n\nThe status filter at the top narrows the list. Beyond filtering to a single status, two convenience options help:\n\n- **All** — every sample.\n- **Open (not yet outcome)** — everything still in the active lifecycle (Requested through Delivered), hiding the Quoted / Lost / Stale outcomes. This is the view managers use to see what's genuinely in flight.\n\n### Where Samples Are Created\n\nThis page is read-and-manage-status only. Reps **request a sample from the lead's detail panel**, where the sample lives functionally. This cross-lead page is for tracking and moving samples through their lifecycle, not creating them.","sections":[]}"""
        });

        // ── Suppression / Do-Not-Contact (Article) ───────────────────────
        await GetOrCreateModule(new TrainingModule
        {
            Title = "Suppression & Do-Not-Contact",
            Slug = "leads-suppression",
            Summary = "The per-channel opt-out and cooldown list: how leads get suppressed, what the channels mean, and how to lift a suppression or clear a cooldown.",
            ContentType = TrainingContentType.Article,
            EstimatedMinutes = 4,
            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 11,
            AppRoutes = """["/leads/suppression"]""",
            Tags = """["leads","suppression","compliance","dnc"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## Suppression & Do-Not-Contact\n\nThe Suppression / Do-Not-Contact page (Leads → Suppression) is where opt-outs and cooldown windows live. It exists so you don't re-contact someone who asked you not to, and so re-contact timing respects the cooldown rules. New opt-outs and cooldowns accumulate here as they're recorded across the system.\n\n### Per-Channel Suppression\n\nSuppression is **per channel**, not all-or-nothing. A lead can opt out of one channel while staying reachable on another:\n\n- **Email opt-out** — don't email this lead.\n- **Call opt-out** — don't call this lead.\n- **SMS opt-out** — don't text this lead.\n\nThe Suppression column on each row shows a red chip for every channel the lead has opted out of. A lead might show an email opt-out but still be callable, for example.\n\n### Cooldowns\n\nSeparate from a hard opt-out is a **cooldown** — a temporary \"don't contact until\" window. A lead in cooldown shows a warning chip with the cooldown-until date and an optional reason code. Cooldowns come from outreach policy (for instance, a campaign's default cooldown override) and the queue/intake logic respects them: a lead still in cooldown is held back from the call queue and skipped during bulk import.\n\n### How Leads Land Here\n\nLeads reach the suppression list a few ways:\n\n- A rep marks a lead **Suppress (DNC)** while working the call queue.\n- An inbound opt-out (an unsubscribe or a do-not-call request) flips the relevant channel flag.\n- An outreach policy or campaign sets a cooldown window.\n\n### Reviewing the List\n\nThe table shows the company, contact, email, phone, the suppression chips, the cooldown-until date, the cooldown reason, and when the preferences were last updated. Clicking a row opens that lead's detail so you can see the full picture.\n\n### Lifting a Suppression\n\nWhen an opt-out was a mistake or the prospect has re-engaged, you can re-enable outreach **one channel at a time** from the row's action buttons:\n\n- **Lift email opt-out** (mail icon) — re-enables email.\n- **Lift call opt-out** (phone icon) — re-enables calling.\n- **Lift SMS opt-out** (sms icon) — re-enables texting.\n\nEach button only appears when that channel is actually suppressed. Lifting one channel leaves the others untouched. The change is recorded in the lead's activity log so there's an audit trail of who re-enabled what.\n\n### Clearing a Cooldown\n\nIf a lead is in a cooldown window you want to end early, the **Clear cooldown** button (schedule icon) removes the cooldown-until date so the lead becomes contactable again immediately. This is independent of the channel opt-outs — clearing a cooldown doesn't touch any opt-out flags.","sections":[]}"""
        });

        // ── Qualification & Classification (Article) ─────────────────────
        await GetOrCreateModule(new TrainingModule
        {
            Title = "Lead Qualification & Classification",
            Slug = "leads-qualification",
            Summary = "Using the classification chips (capability fit, NDA, ITAR/export-control) and reading the engagement-signal strip (playbook hint, recent comms, stale flag) on the lead detail panel.",
            ContentType = TrainingContentType.Article,
            EstimatedMinutes = 5,
            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 12,
            AppRoutes = """["/leads"]""",
            Tags = """["leads","qualification","classification","itar","nda"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## Lead Qualification & Classification\n\nOpen any lead's detail panel and below the basic info you'll find two qualification surfaces: a **classification strip** for tagging the lead's manufacturing and compliance fit, and an **engagement-signal strip** that tells you, at a glance, what to do next. Together they turn a raw contact into a qualified, prioritized opportunity.\n\n### Classification Chips\n\nThe classification strip carries up to four chips. The campaign chip is read-only; the other three are click-to-set — click the chip, pick a value from the menu, and it saves immediately.\n\n**Capability fit** (precision-manufacturing icon) — can your shop actually make what this prospect needs?\n- *Not assessed* — default, nobody has judged it yet.\n- *Fits* — squarely in your wheelhouse.\n- *Needs review* — an engineer should look before you commit.\n- *Doesn't fit* — outside your capabilities; qualify out early rather than waste a quote.\n\n**NDA** (lock icon) — where the non-disclosure agreement stands:\n- *None*, *Requested*, *In force*, *Expired*. Track this so you don't share sensitive specs before an NDA is in force, and so you notice when one lapses.\n\n**ITAR / export control** (public icon) — export-control clearance for defense or controlled work:\n- *N/A*, *Pending*, *Cleared*, *Denied*. For ITAR-controlled work this gate matters before any technical data changes hands.\n\n**Campaign** (campaign icon, read-only) — if the lead came from a bulk-marketing campaign, this chip names it and links to the Campaigns page. It's set at intake and isn't reassigned from the lead.\n\nEach chip color-codes its state so a row of green chips reads very differently from a row with a red \"Doesn't fit\" or \"Denied\". Setting a chip is one click and is logged to the lead's activity timeline.\n\n### The Engagement-Signal Strip\n\nNear the top of the detail body, an engagement strip gives working guidance. It's shown only while the lead is active (hidden once the lead is Converted or Lost, since the guidance no longer applies):\n\n- **Playbook hint** — driven by the lead's engagement shape (Quick quote, Strategic, Prototype, etc.). It reminds you what this kind of deal needs next — e.g., a strategic account's hint nudges you toward mapping the decision-maker and champion.\n- **Recent-engagement chip** — shows a count of recent communications (\"3 recent comms\"), so you know whether the lead has been actively worked or has gone quiet.\n- **Stale badge** — appears when there's been **no activity in the last 14 days**. It's a prompt to follow up or reclassify before the opportunity goes cold.\n\n### Why This Matters\n\nThe classification chips and engagement signals are how a lead earns its place in the work queue. A lead that fits your capabilities, has its NDA in force, is export-clearable, and shows recent engagement is a strong opportunity worth your time. One that doesn't fit, or has gone stale for weeks, is a candidate to qualify out or re-prioritize. Keeping these tags current means the team spends effort where it pays off — and the compliance flags (NDA, ITAR) keep you from sharing controlled information before you're cleared to.","sections":[]}"""
        });

        // ── Advanced Reference (Reference) ───────────────────────────────
        await GetOrCreateModule(new TrainingModule
        {
            Title = "Leads — Advanced Reference",
            Slug = "leads-reference",
            Summary = "Edge-case reference: bulk-intake CSV aliasing + dedup statuses, the call-queue keyboard cheat sheet, the suppression cooldown round-trip, sample stale auto-flagging, the account-deletion block, and engagement-shape JSONB extras.",
            ContentType = TrainingContentType.Reference,
            EstimatedMinutes = 4,
            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 90,
            AppRoutes = """["/leads"]""",
            Tags = """["leads","reference","advanced"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## Leads — Advanced Reference\n\nEdge-case and power-user notes for the Leads area. For everyday workflows see the Overview, Walkthrough, and Field Reference modules; this page documents the ancillary mechanics those modules gloss over.\n\n## Bulk-Intake CSV Column Aliasing & Dedup Statuses\n\nThe bulk-intake parser (`/leads/intake`) matches CSV headers case-insensitively and accepts common aliases — only `companyName` must resolve. The header is lowercased/trimmed, then each logical field picks the first matching alias:\n\n| Field | Accepted header aliases |\n|---|---|\n| companyName | companyname, company, company name, company_name |\n| contactName | contactname, contact, name, contact name, contact_name |\n| email | email, email address, email_address, e-mail |\n| phone | phone, phone number, phone_number, tel, telephone |\n| source | source, lead source, lead_source |\n| notes | notes, note, comment, comments |\n\nAny unrecognized column is ignored. A row is dropped before preview if it has no companyName, email, or phone.\n\nPreview runs every row through ordered gates and labels it with one `BulkLeadIntakeRowStatus`:\n\n- **Created** — passed all gates; inserted on commit.\n- **Invalid** — per-strategy required field missing (cold-call needs phone, cold-email needs email).\n- **MissingRequiredField** — `companyName` blank (the absolute minimum).\n- **DuplicateWithinBatch** — same email or phone appeared earlier in the same file.\n- **DuplicateExistingLead** — email or phone matches an existing Lead (email match is case-insensitive; phone matches on digits-only).\n- **DuplicateExistingContact** — email or phone matches an existing customer Contact (already a customer).\n- **SuppressedOptOut** — the matched Lead/Contact has the relevant channel opt-out for the strategy's channel.\n- **InCooldown** — the matched Lead/Contact has `CooldownUntil > now`, regardless of channel.\n\nCommit inserts only **Created** rows, then re-stamps them with their persisted ids and emits one summary activity row (`Created via bulk intake — strategy: {strategy}`).\n\n## Call-Queue Keyboard Cheat Sheet\n\nThe Worker Queue (`/leads/queue`) is keyboard-first. Letter keys fire dispositions; J/K navigate. Shortcuts are ignored while the disposition-notes box is focused, so typing is never intercepted.\n\n| Key | Disposition (state) | Effect |\n|---|---|---|\n| E | Engaged | Exits queue, flips Lead to Contacted. |\n| N | NoAnswer | Re-queues for retry. |\n| V | VoicemailLeft | Re-queues for retry. |\n| C | CallbackScheduled | Opens callback scheduler; commits on confirm. |\n| B | BadData | Marks the Lead lost (wrong number / bounce). |\n| S | Suppressed | Operator DNC; routes to suppression list. |\n| J | (navigate) | Advance to next lead in the pulled slice. |\n| K | (navigate) | Back to previous lead in the slice. |\n\nEach disposition is one POST plus automatic advance. Pulled slices are disjoint across reps, so two reps never land on the same lead.\n\n## Suppression Cooldown Round-Trip\n\nOutreach preferences (`UpdateLeadOutreachPreferences`) auto-create a preferences row on first non-null write and are channel-independent. Each opt-out toggle stamps three fields together:\n\n- Setting `EmailOptOut`/`CallOptOut`/`SmsOptOut` to true also stamps `{channel}OptOutAt = now` and `{channel}OptOutSource`; setting it false clears both — logged as `{channel}-opt-out-set` / `{channel}-opt-out-cleared`.\n- **Cooldown** is a separate, channel-agnostic window. Writing `CooldownUntil` logs `cooldown-set`; writing it null logs `cooldown-cleared`. `CooldownReasonCode` and `CooldownNotes` ride alongside.\n\nThe round-trip: a rep suppresses a channel (or a cooldown is applied via campaign policy), it blocks that channel in the queue and intake (`CooldownUntil > now` ⇒ InCooldown), and the suppression page lifts it one channel at a time or clears the cooldown — each lift/clear is an independent change written back to the same preferences row and audited on the lead's activity log.\n\n## Sample Stale Auto-Flagging\n\n`MarkStaleSamplesJob` is a nightly Hangfire sweep. It flips `SampleShipment.Status` from **Delivered** to **Stale** when `DeliveredAt` is older than the `StaleThresholdDays` threshold (14 days) with no follow-up outcome (no QuotedFromSample / LostFromSample transition). Each flip logs `sample-marked-stale` on the owning Lead. The 14-day window is a deliberate evaluate-vs-attention compromise and is admin-configurable. Reps can still mark Stale by hand from the sample's outcome menu; this job just catches the ones that went quiet.\n\n## Account-Deletion Block\n\n`DeleteAccountHandler` soft-deletes a B2B Account but **refuses** while any Lead still references it: `Cannot delete account — {n} lead(s) reference it. Unassign the account on each lead first.` (`InvalidOperationException` ⇒ 409). This keeps the back-link intact for audit history — the same defensive pattern as LeadSource. Unassign the account on the referencing leads (or let them convert / be lost), then retry. Converted leads no longer count against the block.\n\n## Engagement-Shape JSONB Extras\n\nA lead carries two shape-related fields. `EngagementShape` (`LeadEngagementShape` enum: Unknown=0, QuickQuote=1, Repeat=2, Strategic=3, Prototype) records which New-Lead fork shape created it; **Unknown** is the Quick-add / legacy default. The shape-specific extras (parts/qty, target price, needed-by date, decision-maker, champion, current vendor, project type, timeline) are serialized into `Lead.CustomFieldValues` — a single nullable string column holding a JSON bag — so new shapes can add fields without a schema change. Only filled extras are stored; empty ones are dropped. On create, the shape is appended to the activity description as a ` [{EngagementShape}]` fragment (omitted for Unknown). The detail panel reads the shape to drive the engagement-signal playbook hint.","sections":[]}"""
        });

        Log.Information("Seeded Leads training modules");
    }
}
